    >> Anonymous 01/07/07(Sun)01:38 No.1701191
    >>1700903
    Well first off there's a bit of a problem with the pencil smudging.

    Usually (this example is for Photoshop CS), I'd scan in an image at about 300dpi with Color (because it's easier to clean up than greyscale which leaves in smudges completely). Then I'd hit CTRL+L to bring up the layers pallet and move the arrows. The white arrow on the left makes the whites whiter. The black arrow on the right makes the blacks SHOOPer. This usually works to clean up an image of smudges while darkening up the lines.

    HOWEVER! The smudges are almost as dark as the lines in this image. So using the layers pallete just darkens up the smudges. Either re-scan in your image at a higher rez or clean up the smudges with a gum-eraser.

    It depends on what program you use to do your image editing too. There's different keycombos/menus/etc. in play.
